1.) describe the null and alternative hypotheses for the chosen example;
The null hypothesis states that there is no effect, difference, or relationship between variables. The alternative hypothesis is the opposite. It suggests there is an effect, difference, or relationship between variables in the population. 

2.) explain the meaning of a type 1 error (i.e., a "false positive") in the chosen context;
Occurs when you reject the null hypothesis when it is actually true. 

3.) explain the meaning of a type 2 error (i.e., a "false negative") in the chosen context;
Occurs when you fail to reject the null hypothesis when it is actually false. 

4.) describe the potential consequences associated with each type of wrong decision (i.e., type 1 or type 2 error).
The consequences associated with the wrong decision of a type 1 error would lead to incorrect decisions based on the assumption that there's an effect or difference when there isn't. The consequences associated with the wrong decision of a type 2 error would lead to the acceptance of something as not significant or different when it is.
